At the big-picture level, you already have the core breakthrough captured:

not a theme park, but a persistent participatory world.

That’s the important part.

From here, the highest-value additions to the repo are probably not endless feature ideas, but:

* foundational principles,
* operating doctrines,
* system invariants,
* experience architecture,
* economic philosophy,
* immersion heuristics,
* recursive improvement loops.

Those are the reusable parts.

That said, there are a few major missing “pillar” ideas worth capturing before you zoom out.

⸻

1. MULTISENSORY WORLD DESIGN DOCTRINE

This is huge.

The park should not just be:
seen.

It should be:

* heard
* smelled
* touched
* spatially navigated
* socially experienced
* physically embodied

Core invariant:

immersion increases when multiple sensory channels reinforce the same narrative frame.

Examples:

* warm volcanic air in fire zones
* cool mist near water Pokémon
* berry scents in forests
* floor vibration during legendary encounters
* distant cries echoing through caves
* reactive lighting synced to events

This becomes:

sensory coherence engineering.

Very reusable concept.

⸻

2. “THE WORLD CONTINUES WITHOUT YOU” PRINCIPLE

Critical.

The park should feel:
alive independently of the guest.

Examples:

* NPCs have routines
* Pokémon interact with each other
* events happen without player triggers
* weather changes naturally
* migrations occur
* stores close/open dynamically
* ranger reports evolve

Core invariant:

persistent worlds feel real when they exhibit autonomous continuity.

This is huge for AI systems generally.

⸻

3. PARTICIPATORY IDENTITY SYSTEMS

Guests are not spectators.
They become:

* trainers
* collectors
* researchers
* rangers
* breeders
* battlers
* explorers

Core invariant:

identity deepens immersion more than spectacle alone.

This applies far beyond parks.

⸻

4. DISCOVERY DENSITY

One of the biggest hidden variables.

You want:
small discoveries everywhere.

Examples:

* hidden figurines
* secret sounds
* environmental easter eggs
* hidden lore
* tiny Pokémon tracks
* reactive NPC dialogue
* invisible shortcuts
* changing details

Core invariant:

dense layered discovery creates perceived world depth.

Very important pattern.

⸻

5. POSITIVE-SUM IMMERSION ECONOMICS

This deserves explicit formalization.

Core idea:
A sufficiently rich world can monetize:

* participation,
* attachment,
* continuity,
* craftsmanship,
* community,
    without requiring predatory extraction.

Core invariant:

abundance of meaningful surfaces reduces pressure for exploitative monetization.

That’s a major philosophical/business insight.

⸻

6. WORLD-AS-INTERFACE

Another huge one.

The environment itself becomes UI.

Examples:

* HM gates
* environmental puzzles
* visual pathfinding
* Pokémon cries as signals
* lighting cues
* terrain shaping
* dynamic NPC hints

Core invariant:

the best interfaces disappear into the world itself.

This is applicable everywhere:
AI, AR, education, cities, games.

⸻

7. SOCIAL ARCHITECTURE

You touched this but it deserves its own section.

The park intentionally creates:

* cooperation
* trading
* shared discoveries
* collaborative events
* crowd rituals
* team identity
* social storytelling

Core invariant:

worlds become sticky when people form memories together inside them.

Not just alone.

⸻

8. MEMORY ANCHOR DESIGN

Very important.

Objects become:
memory crystallization points.

Examples:

* gym badges
* trainer cards
* region passports
* collectible tokens
* photos
* stamped journals
* personalized Pokédex histories

Core invariant:

physical artifacts amplify emotional continuity.

This explains why merch works when done correctly.

⸻

9. “MYSTERY RESERVE”

This one is subtle but extremely important.

Never fully explain everything.

Always leave:

* hidden myths
* unresolved rumors
* impossible sightings
* unexplained events
* ultra-rare encounters

Core invariant:

mystery preserves long-term curiosity.

Over-optimization kills magic.

⸻

10. THE BIGGEST REPO-WORTHY INSIGHT

Probably this:

“Immersive worlds are recursive meaning engines.”

They:

* generate behavior,
* shape identity,
* produce memories,
* create attachment,
* reveal patterns,
* extract invariants,
* improve themselves through interaction.

That’s the deep abstraction underneath the whole discussion.

